\section{What omitted blocks and terms mean}{

\code{exchangeable_rescov()} only describes constraints that were already imposed
when the model was fitted. It does not remove a block, set a variance to zero,
or otherwise constrain the supplied model. Describe only the structure that
was actually fitted.

If a term occurs in only one selected block, the function represents the
missing coordinate as a structural zero:
\itemize{
\item A term present only in \code{shared} has no difference component, so the two
members have identical random effects for that term.
\item A term present only in \code{difference} has no shared component, so the two
members have equal-magnitude, opposite-sign random effects for that term.
}

Setting \code{difference = NULL} or \code{shared = NULL} applies the corresponding rule
to the entire omitted block. This is valid only when that block is truly
absent from the fitted model. Do not use \code{NULL} merely to ignore an existing
block; the resulting back-transformation would be incorrect.

See the constrained-block example in the
\href{https://pascal-kueng.github.io/interdep/articles/apim.html#fitted-constraints-and-omitted-blocks}{exchangeable APIM vignette}.
}

\section{Backend note}{

In \code{brms}, cross-sectional and same-occasion partner dependence can be
represented directly with
\code{unstr(time = member_position, gr = residual_group)}. With Gaussian
outcomes, \code{sigma ~ 1} supplies the common residual scale. Non-Gaussian
families have no \code{sigma} parameter here; \code{unstr()} instead estimates a
common latent residual scale and correlation on the linear-predictor scale.
Here,
\code{member_position} identifies the same two arbitrary positions within every
group, and \code{residual_group} identifies dyads in cross-sectional data or
dyad-occasions in longitudinal data. This direct specification applies when
one covariance structure is sufficient. Separate composition-specific
\code{unstr()} structures for mixed dyad types are not currently supported in a
standard single-response \code{brms} model. For Gaussian mixed-dyad residual
covariance, use \code{glmmTMB}. Shared/difference blocks remain relevant for
higher-level random effects and can represent latent link-scale covariance
in non-Gaussian models.
}

